<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-11-18T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-11-18T16:00:00-05:00" n="412" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d412">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 841.857/190</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Chargé in Germcmy</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJC1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-11-18T16:00:00-05:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">November 18, 1916, 4 p. m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>3589. Department advised that P. &amp; O. liner <hi rend="italic">Arabia</hi> carrying some 480 passengers, including about 170
                                women and children and also some Americans, was torpedoed without
                                warning November 6 in Mediterranean on her homeward trip by German
                                or Austrian submarine. It appears that the weather was fine and that
                                the submarine, before dispatching the torpedo, could have seen women
                                and children on the deck. This Government is unable to square this
                                disaster with the German assurance of May 4, 1916, which, it is
                                understood, binds both Central powers. Please bring this case to
                                attention of Government to which you are accredited and request an
                                immediate investigation and prompt report in this case.</p>
                            <p>Repeat Vienna, No. 1424.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>